Occupy Wall Street Protesters Rally Against "Excessive Force"
By: Nicole Ward


Their battle over company greed isn't always over yet, however protesters who've been camped out in Lower Manhattan for two weeks are now taking on a new issue.
Demonstrators marched from their major gathering point in Zuccotti Park to police headquarters Friday to shine mild on what they say is excessive force used by way of the department.
Several human beings were maced and about 80 humans arrested for disorderly behavior final weekend.
The branch is now investigating.
Protesters said that human beings in positions of authority need to no longer abuse their power.
"I saw what took place to the humans getting sprayed with pepper spray and them making an attempt to alter people's proper to free speech, the right to assemble," stated one protester.
"The humans that are here, you know, we desire to make a difference, we desire to make changes," said another.
For the first time, a important labor union joined the protest, which has since moved lower back to Zuccotti Park.
Transport Workers Local one hundred representatives say the state's wealthiest residents ought to pay their honest share.
"We sense it is additionally unjust, you recognize the fat cats get fatter and the bad get poorer," stated supervisor Taul Flores of the Transport Workers Union. "We just choose our fair share like anybody else.